Neutrinoless double-beta decay is a hypothetical nuclear decay that can only occur if neutrinos, neutral elementary particles with the distinction of having tiny masses, have certain exotic quantum mechanical properties.   In particular neutrinos need to have wave-functions with only two components, much simpler than the wave-functions of -say- electrons.  Only neutrinoless double-beta decay can test this property, as far as we know, but, in addition, the rate of the decay effectively measures the neutrino mass, in a way that is substantially more accurate than other methods.
With partial support from this grant the EXO collaboration published the first results from EXO-200, a 200kg experiment in which the double-beta decay of the isotope 136 of xenon is searched for.  The EXO-200 detector, shown in the first image, was built out of very special materials that resulted in the lowest radioactive background ever obtained.  This is important because the double-beta decay is so rare that natural radioactivity contained in all ordinary objects would confuse the measurement.   In fact the experiment is installed deep underground, in DOEÆs WIPP facility in New Mexico, to shield away the cosmic radiation that would disturb the measurement.  In the first set of measurements EXO-200 has not observed the neutrinoless double beta decay and has set a limit of 1.6x10^25 years for the half-life of this decay.  This corresponds to about a million-billion times the age of the Universe.  This, in turn, corresponds to neutrino masses to be smaller than 0.140 to 0.380 eV (electron-volts), or at least a million times lighter than the second lightest particle, the electron, with mass 500,000eV.    EXO-200 is collecting more data and will have an updated result soon.
This grant mainly supported the initial development of a 25 times larger experiment, dubbed nEXO, that will push the sensitivity to neutrino masses to the 0.01eV region.   A sketch of nEXO is presented in the second image.  Some of the technologies developed for EXO-200 and nEXO can be transferred to other fields of science and technology, in particular radiation detection for medical diagnostics and security.  In addition nEXO will require large amounts of isotopically separated Xenon.  This will be produced in collaboration with Russia, with implications in the area of international cooperation.


